<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>AFS0095</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">AFS0095</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Written evidence submitted by Conal McCoy</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Introduction:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Academy schools are a clear point of consensus between the current government and the previous government. However, this in no way entails that the Coalition Government have kept Labour’s idea for the programme completely intact. The Coalition wants to lea</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ve its mark on the programme and has done so through its wide ranging expansion of the programme. This submission of evidence aims to examine, primarily, how effective the academy schools programme has been, both since its inception under Labour and during</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> its expansion under the Coalition, in narrowing the gap for disadvantaged children. It takes the view that, whilst much can be said in credit to the programme, it has not achieved this aim and far more needs to be done. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The Problem</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> Stated:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In most ins</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tances of government initiatives, problems usually emerge from their implementation and running on the ground. However, in the case of the academies programme, it seems that its problems also lie in the crafting of its design. The biggest problem lies in t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he expansion of the programme, already alluded to, under the Coalition. Due to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the success of the programme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> current</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> government felt that academy schooling should be open to all and not just the underperforming. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Owing to this, it has allowed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> all school</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s to opt out of local authority control</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and convert into academies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, giving priority</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to those judged ‘outstanding’ by Ofsted. The second problem that this submission shall examine resides in the admissions process. Having complete autonomy from local author</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ity control, academies are able to select up to 10% of their admissions based on aptitude, should they wish, leading to obvious implications on the attainment gap between disadvantaged children and their peers. The final problem that that this submission s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hall turn</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> its</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> attention to is the inherent system</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">at</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ic bias that academy schooling has towards mi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ddle class pupils. In outlining</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the in-built flaws of the programme, this submission </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">shall now</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> examine</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> their consequences in practice.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Following this, it shall </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">recommend some solutions.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The Consequences:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Illustrating how the government’s expansion of the programme </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">has not been effective in narrowing the gap for disadvantaged children, this submission refers to a report conducted by the National Audit Office</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> (N</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">AO)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in 2010. It found that on average, the gap in attainment between the more disadvantaged pupils and their peers has in fact grown wider in academies than in maintained schools. This leads it to conclude that any inc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">reases in academy performance are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> driv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">en by t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he significant improvements of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the less disadvantaged pupils.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Reinforcing this view, a comparative study conducted by Machin and Vernoit found that in those academies opened</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> under the Coalition</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in September 2010, nearly 80% of their pupils were ach</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ieving 5 or more A*-C grades at GCSE in 2008</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, before conversion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In contrast, about only</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 35% of pupils</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in the academies opened under Labour, a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">chieved this requirement in 2008.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This statistical evidence suggests that the expansion of the academies programme has been ineffective in narrowing the gap for disadvantaged children. Furthermore, it seems that in shifting attention from underperforming schools to high-performing schools,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the government has completely departed from the original aims of the programme espoused by the previous government. This submission is of the view that rewarding such high-performing schools with the financial gains of academy conversion is hardly justifi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">able </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> times of economic austerity. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Signalling a mismatch in priority further,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the Committee of Public Acco</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">unts</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> reports</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that some of the budgets the Department for Education used to fund this expansion were initially supposed to be for other purposes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> such</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the £95 million intended for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">improving underperforming schools.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> In such economically stringent times as these, being given a report of ‘outstanding’ from Ofsted should be enough in and of itself. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In addition, one cannot help but be suspicious of the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> programme’s expansion due to the way that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">education secretary</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> portrayed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> it both in public and in Parliament. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Following the General Election in 2010, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Mr Gove claimed that over 1,000 schools had applied to become academies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, when in reality, this number </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">was much smaller at 153.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Furthermore, others have accused him of ‘railroading’ the legislation for the subsequent Academies Act of 2010, in only allowing three days for its passage in the House of Commons.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The fact that Mr Gove was so keen to get the bil</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">l </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">through Parliament sheds lights on why the expansion of the programme has not been effective in narrowing the gap for disadvantaged children. As previously hinted in the introduction, one of the reasons for the government’s mismatch in priorities could b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e due to it simply wanting to leave a mark during its time in office. The Conservatives, in particular, were supportive of the academies programme since its inception under Labour. But nonetheless, they want to show the public that they are different from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Labour </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and are doing this by changing a programme in no need of changing. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This submission now turns its attention to how the admissions process of academy schools has done little to narrow the gap for disadvantaged children.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Able to select up to 10% of their intake based on ‘aptitude’, academies have in practice offloaded disruptive pupils to neighbouring schools. Confirming</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> this, the NAO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> has observed that 74% of those academies surveyed said they participate in local authori</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ty ‘fair access’ protocol, which includes admitting those with challenging behaviour even if this exceeds agreed admissions.</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Whilst this shows that the majority are abiding by the rules and procedures governing admissions, it also indicates that a signifi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cant number are not. A significant number would prefer to change the children than change </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">their teaching methods, and they do this at the expense of the disadvantaged.</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> To add to this, academies are increasing the ‘quality’ of their pupil intake in Year 7.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> According to Machin and Vernoit, there has been a significant increase in Key Stage 2 scores for Year 7 pupils that have enrolled into an academy.</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As well as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> admitting only those with an existing level of attainment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, academies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> also seem to be admitting</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> fewer pupils from working class families. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In 2005, The Guardian reported that the percentage of pupils admitted from less affluent families had dropped in nearly two-thirds of all academies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Over six years down the line, Wrigley and Kalambouka find that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">academy schools are shedding three-quarters of their disadvantaged pupils, intimating that the problem is worsening. They give the example that some academies are using certain devices to deter ‘less desirable’ pupils such as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">very expensive uniforms with c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ompulsory sports kits costing over £110</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">But perhaps the more widely used measure of the social composition of pupils being admitted into academies is the proportion of those eligible for free school meals. To this, Machin and Vernoit note that this amou</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nts to 27.5%</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> those pupils in academies under Labour in 2008. In stark contrast, once again, this amounts to just over a modest 5%</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in the same year for those</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> schools which became academies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 2 years later</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> under the Coalition.</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> This suggests that academies are exploiting their privilege in being able to select up to 10% of admissions. They are using this both to select only the most able and only those from a more affluent background. The combination of these admissions preferen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ces further widens the g</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ap for disadvantaged children and whilst such malpractices occurred under Labour also, the Coalition’s decision to expand th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e programme has not aided</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the problem.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The last problem that this submission devotes attention to is an </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">offshoot of the flawed admissions process of academy schooling which is its systematic bias towards pupils from middle class backgrounds. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A government commissioned report by consultants Pricewaterhouse Coopers, as far back as 2005, found that the biggest b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eneficiaries of academy schools tend to be middle class families.</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> In analysis of this, Perry and Francis hold that this is because </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">middle class parents have the financial resources to move house to access catchment of the latest high-performing academy. T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">heir increased cultural capital means that they also have well-resourced networks to know the ‘rules of the game’, understanding the way the system works and the hierarchies therein.</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This criticism applies, if not more so, to free schools as well. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Harris espou</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ses the view that free schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> attract</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> only middle class parents for it is they who have the time and resources for effective involvement in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">their establishment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This claim was apparent even before the free schools programme was implemented in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> England, when the government relied heavily on its experience in other countries. For instance, research in Public Policy too found that those who benefitted the most from the free schools scheme in Sweden were those from educated professional homes.</span><a name="_ftnref15"></a><a href="#_ftn15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Cla</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ire Bradford, the head teacher of Henbury School in Bristol made her anxiety clear to the BBC when she said that a proposed free school will lure children from privileged backgro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">unds away from her school.</span><a name="_ftnref16"></a><a href="#_ftn16">[16]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Consequently, it seems from this that academy sch</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ools, in their present state, are not effective in narrowing the gap for disadvantaged children. Whilst disadvantaged children, being those who on average fall behind in attainment compared to their peers, do not always happen to be those from deprived bac</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">kgrounds, there is certainly a correlation in that direction. Therefore, it is highly questionable, that a programme which sought out to improve the attainment of the disadvantaged has, in practice, only further propelled the already advantaged. This submi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ssion has demonstrated, then, that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">through its expansion, its admissions process and its inherent loopholes, the academies programme has been ineffective in narrowing the gap for disadvantaged children. The current government have misplaced their targeted </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">demographic for the programme.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">What can be done?:</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Having demonstrated the problems and resultant implications of the academies programme, this submission now lays out some solutions. In its critical approach, this submission does not, nonetheless, want to jump to the conclusion that no academies have narr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">owed the gap for disadvantaged children. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Some academies have performed better than others, and this seems most notable amongst those established earlier. Machin and Vernoit find that the early academy conversions witnessed a more significant increase in Ke</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y Stage 4 performance than the later academy conversions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref17"></a><a href="#_ftn17">[17]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Naturally, it must be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">considered what it is that the earlier conversions have which the later ones do not and the answer must be more than just the fact that they have ‘stood the test of time’. It </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is highly likely, that their increased academic performance is due to their higher levels of curricular autonomy which became limited somewhat after 2007 when they had to teach the national curriculum in English, Maths and Science</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> This submission, then, s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">uggests that in order to narrow the gap for disadvantaged children, academies should be given back some of their original curricular autonomy for this allows them to respond flexibly to pupil needs. Educational routes beyond the exclusively academic </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">need t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> valued. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">An additional suggestion </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">comprises</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">those academies who are not performing so well should learn off of those who are. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Whilst this is indeed existing government policy, this submission echoes the point made in a report by the Education Co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mmittee that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> this type of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> coll</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ab</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">oration is particularly useful</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for narrowing the gap between the advantaged and disadvantaged.</span><a name="_ftnref18"></a><a href="#_ftn18">[18]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It adds that collaboration is most effective where members are located in geographical proximity for this makes it easier to mov</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e expertise around</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. This submission advises also that the Department rectifies the sheer amount of bureaucracy in the way of such collaboration, for this has been identified as a barrier by Nottingham City Council.</span><a name="_ftnref19"></a><a href="#_ftn19">[19]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> A final point should be made with regards to transparency and in this light, a recommendation made by the Sutton Trust seems most pertinent. This holds that there should be a measure in league tables signalling the extent to which an academy is narrowing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the gap for disadvantaged children.</span><a name="_ftnref20"></a><a href="#_ftn20">[20]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">[Words: 1976]</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">National Audit Office, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Department for Education: The Academies Programme</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">, (London, The</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Stationery Office, 2010)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">, p. 27.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Stephen Machin and James Vernoit, ‘Academy schools: who benefits?’,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">CentrePiece </spa